  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (848bb44 2022-12-28T00:07:21.178449984Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nforge fmt\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen writing a comment inside the parenthesis of a statement (like an `if`), and just before a built-in variable (such as `msg.value`, `block.timestamp`, or `block.coinbase`), this comment will put right after the `msg` or `block` depending on the context, and before the dot linking with the next word. This does not look very pretty, altough compiling well.\r\n\r\nConsider this example:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\npragma solidity 0.8.0;\r\n\r\ncontract Format {\r\n    bool public test;\r\n\r\n    function testing(uint256 amount) public payable {\r\n        if (\r\n            // This is a comment\r\n            msg.value == amount\r\n        ) {\r\n            test = true;\r\n        } else {\r\n            test = false;\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (\r\n            // Another one\r\n            block.timestamp >= amount\r\n        ) {}\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen run a little `forge fmt`\r\n\r\nThis results in:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\npragma solidity 0.8.0;\r\n\r\ncontract Format {\r\n    bool public test;\r\n\r\n    function testing(uint256 amount) public payable {\r\n        if (\r\n            msg\r\n                // This is a comment\r\n                .value == amount\r\n        ) {\r\n            test = true;\r\n        } else {\r\n            test = false;\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (\r\n            block\r\n                // Another one\r\n                .timestamp >= amount\r\n        ) {}\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nwhich does not look pretty.\r\n\r\nI can have a look a this in a PR if you guys agree.\r\n\r\nThanks !",
